full_text:
EVP itself defies categorization. Some folks think it is a modulated em field in proximity to the microphone. There is evidence to support this, as evp has been recorded in faraday cages and vacuum jars. It would then be logical to assume that evp is independent of vibratory sound waves. Then that is blown to hell when you consider that Waldemar Bogoras is credited with the first reported evp capture while recording rituals of the Tchoutki tribe in Siberia in 1901. The was with a mechanical gramaphone-like device, no microphone, just a horn to amplify sound, mechanical &quot;write&quot; needle, and wax cylinder. Electric gramaphones didn&#39;t come about till almost the &#39;20s. In that case it would appear that evp exists as soundwaves and not em fields.

Which one is right? Both probably, and that isn&#39;t even taking into account the mechanism involved in box-related evp.

Intent and desire to communicate. The rest works itself out.

Thanks
Andy







--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, Rj &lt;rasterer@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I hear different people proposing different mechanisms by which EVP operates. Some say it uses the words in radio transmissions, and anyone can hear it if they listen. Some say it uses the disturbance or energy of radio transmissions to form new words, but it is harder to hear (some say you have to be &quot;chosen&quot; to hear it). Some say it can use any transmission, and can even be seen in video. Some say it doesn&#39;t require any transmission, and can be extracted from white noise, or no noise. Some say it can be heard even in things like running water.
&gt; 
&gt; So it depends on which theory this person is testing. If he were testing the claim that the EVPs required a radio broadcast, then this test wouldn&#39;t be good, since the Faraday cage should block the radio needed. If he is testing the one where people claim that words appear on a radio or recording device that have not been transmitted, then this sounds like a reaonsable test to me. 
